text: ﻿CHAPTER I.
label: neutral

text: Down the Rabbit-Hole
label: neutral

text:
Alice was beginning to get very tired of sitting by her sister on the
bank, and of having nothing to do: once or twice she had peeped into
the book her sister was reading, but it had no pictures or
conversations in it, “and what is the use of a book,” thought Alice
“without pictures or conversations?”
label: disgust

text:
So she was considering in her own mind (as well as she could, for the
hot day made her feel very sleepy and stupid), whether the pleasure of
making a daisy-chain would be worth the trouble of getting up and
picking the daisies, when suddenly a White Rabbit with pink eyes ran
close by her.
label: sadness

text:
There was nothing so _very_ remarkable in that; nor did Alice think it
so _very_ much out of the way to hear the Rabbit say to itself, “Oh
dear!
label: surprise

text: Oh dear!
label: surprise

text:
I shall be late!” (when she thought it over afterwards,
it occurred to her that she ought to have wondered at this, but at the
time it all seemed quite natural); but when the Rabbit actually _took a
watch out of its waistcoat-pocket_, and looked at it, and then hurried
on, Alice started to her feet, for it flashed across her mind that she
had never before seen a rabbit with either a waistcoat-pocket, or a
watch to take out of it, and burning with curiosity, she ran across the
field after it, and fortunately was just in time to see it pop down a
large rabbit-hole under the hedge.
label: surprise

text:
In another moment down went Alice after it, never once considering how
in the world she was to get out again.
label: surprise

text:
The rabbit-hole went straight on like a tunnel for some way, and then
dipped suddenly down, so suddenly that Alice had not a moment to think
about stopping herself before she found herself falling down a very
deep well.
label: surprise

text:
Either the well was very deep, or she fell very slowly, for she had
plenty of time as she went down to look about her and to wonder what
was going to happen next.
label: surprise

text:
First, she tried to look down and make out
what she was coming to, but it was too dark to see anything; then she
looked at the sides of the well, and noticed that they were filled with
cupboards and book-shelves; here and there she saw maps and pictures
hung upon pegs.
label: surprise

text:
She took down a jar from one of the shelves as she
passed; it was labelled “ORANGE MARMALADE”, but to her great
disappointment it was empty: she did not like to drop the jar for fear
of killing somebody underneath, so managed to put it into one of the
cupboards as she fell past it.
label: fear

text:
“Well!” thought Alice to herself, “after such a fall as this, I shall
think nothing of tumbling down stairs!
label: anger

text:
How brave they’ll all think me
at home!
label: joy

text:
Why, I wouldn’t say anything about it, even if I fell off the
top of the house!” (Which was very likely true.)
label: anger

text: Down, down, down.
label: neutral

label: neutral

text:
“I wonder how
many miles I’ve fallen by this time?” she said aloud.
label: surprise

text:
“I must be
getting somewhere near the centre of the earth.
label: neutral

text:
Let me see: that would
be four thousand miles down, I think—” (for, you see, Alice had learnt
several things of this sort in her lessons in the schoolroom, and
though this was not a _very_ good opportunity for showing off her
knowledge, as there was no one to listen to her, still it was good
practice to say it over) “—yes, that’s about the right distance—but
then I wonder what Latitude or Longitude I’ve got to?” (Alice had no
idea what Latitude was, or Longitude either, but thought they were nice
grand words to say.)
label: neutral

Please, Ma’am, is this New Zealand or Australia?”

talking again.

But do cats eat bats, I wonder?” And here

Do cats eat bats?” and
sometimes, “Do bats eat cats?” for, you see, as she couldn’t answer

She felt

down she came upon a heap of sticks and dry leaves, and

text:
Alice was not a bit hurt, and she jumped up on to her feet in a moment:
she looked up, but it was all dark overhead; before her was another
long passage, and the White Rabbit was still in sight, hurrying down
it.
label: fear

text:
There was not a moment to be lost: away went Alice like the wind,
and was just in time to hear it say, as it turned a corner, “Oh my ears
and whiskers, how late it’s getting!” She was close behind it when she
turned the corner, but the Rabbit was no longer to be seen: she found
herself in a long, low hall, which was lit up by a row of lamps hanging
from the roof.
label: surprise

text:
There were doors all round the hall, but they were all locked; and when
Alice had been all the way down one side and up the other, trying every
door, she walked sadly down the middle, wondering how she was ever to
get out again.
label: surprise

text:
Suddenly she came upon a little three-legged table, all made of solid
glass; there was nothing on it except a tiny golden key, and Alice’s
first thought was that it might belong to one of the doors of the hall;
but, alas!
label: surprise

text:
either the locks were too large, or the key was too small,
but at any rate it would not open any of them.
label: neutral

text:
However, on the second
time round, she came upon a low curtain she had not noticed before, and
behind it was a little door about fifteen inches high: she tried the
little golden key in the lock, and to her great delight it fitted!
label: surprise

text:
Alice opened the door and found that it led into a small passage, not
much larger than a rat-hole: she knelt down and looked along the
passage into the loveliest garden you ever saw.
label: surprise

text:
How she longed to get
out of that dark hall, and wander about among those beds of bright
flowers and those cool fountains, but she could not even get her head
through the doorway; “and even if my head would go through,” thought
poor Alice, “it would be of very little use without my shoulders.
label: neutral

text:
Oh,
how I wish I could shut up like a telescope!
label: surprise

text:
I think I could, if I only
knew how to begin.” For, you see, so many out-of-the-way things had
happened lately, that Alice had begun to think that very few things
indeed were really impossible.
label: surprise

text:
There seemed to be no use in waiting by the little door, so she went
back to the table, half hoping she might find another key on it, or at
any rate a book of rules for shutting people up like telescopes: this
time she found a little bottle on it, (“which certainly was not here
before,” said Alice,) and round the neck of the bottle was a paper
label, with the words “DRINK ME,” beautifully printed on it in large
letters.
label: neutral

text:
It was all very well to say “Drink me,” but the wise little Alice was
not going to do _that_ in a hurry.
label: neutral

text:
“No, I’ll look first,” she said,
“and see whether it’s marked ‘_poison_’ or not”; for she had read
several nice little histories about children who had got burnt, and
eaten up by wild beasts and other unpleasant things, all because they
_would_ not remember the simple rules their friends had taught them:
such as, that a red-hot poker will burn you if you hold it too long;
and that if you cut your finger _very_ deeply with a knife, it usually
bleeds; and she had never forgotten that, if you drink much from a
bottle marked “poison,” it is almost certain to disagree with you,
sooner or later.
label: neutral

text:
However, this bottle was _not_ marked “poison,” so Alice ventured to
taste it, and finding it very nice, (it had, in fact, a sort of mixed
flavour of cherry-tart, custard, pine-apple, roast turkey, toffee, and
hot buttered toast,) she very soon finished it off.
label: neutral

text:
“What a curious feeling!” said Alice; “I must be shutting up like a
telescope.”
label: surprise

text:
And so it was indeed: she was now only ten inches high, and her face
brightened up at the thought that she was now the right size for going
through the little door into that lovely garden.
label: joy

text:
First, however, she
waited for a few minutes to see if she was going to shrink any further:
she felt a little nervous about this; “for it might end, you know,”
said Alice to herself, “in my going out altogether, like a candle.
label: fear

text:
I
wonder what I should be like then?” And she tried to fancy what the
flame of a candle is like after the candle is blown out, for she could
not remember ever having seen such a thing.
label: surprise

text:
After a while, finding that nothing more happened, she decided on going
into the garden at once; but, alas for poor Alice!
label: sadness

text:
when she got to the
door, she found she had forgotten the little golden key, and when she

and when she had tired herself out with trying, the poor little thing
sat down and cried.
label: sadness

text:
“Come, there’s no use in crying like that!” said Alice to herself,
rather sharply; “I advise you to leave off this minute!” She generally
gave herself very good advice, (though she very seldom followed it),
and sometimes she scolded herself so severely as to bring tears into
her eyes; and once she remembered trying to box her own ears for having
cheated herself in a game of croquet she was playing against herself,
for this curious child was very fond of pretending to be two people.
label: anger

text:
“But it’s no use now,” thought poor Alice, “to pretend to be two
people!
label: anger

text:
Why, there’s hardly enough of me left to make _one_ respectable
person!”
label: surprise

text:
Soon her eye fell on a little glass box that was lying under the table:
she opened it, and found in it a very small cake, on which the words
“EAT ME” were beautifully marked in currants.
label: neutral

text:
“Well, I’ll eat it,” said
Alice, “and if it makes me grow larger, I can reach the key; and if it
makes me grow smaller, I can creep under the door; so either way I’ll
get into the garden, and I don’t care which happens!”
label: anger

text: She ate a little bit, and said anxiously to herself, “Which way?
label: fear

text:
Which
way?”, holding her hand on the top of her head to feel which way it was
growing, and she was quite surprised to find that she remained the same
size: to be sure, this generally happens when one eats cake, but Alice
had got so much into the way of expecting nothing but out-of-the-way
things to happen, that it seemed quite dull and stupid for life to go
on in the common way.
label: surprise

text: So she set to work, and very soon finished off the cake.
label: joy

text: CHAPTER III.
label: neutral

text: A Caucus-Race and a Long Tale
label: neutral

text:
They were indeed a queer-looking party that assembled on the bank—the
birds with draggled feathers, the animals with their fur clinging close
to them, and all dripping wet, cross, and uncomfortable.
label: disgust

text:
The first question of course was, how to get dry again: they had a
consultation about this, and after a few minutes it seemed quite
natural to Alice to find herself talking familiarly with them, as if
she had known them all her life.
label: neutral

text:
Indeed, she had quite a long argument
with the Lory, who at last turned sulky, and would only say, “I am
older than you, and must know better;” and this Alice would not allow
without knowing how old it was, and, as the Lory positively refused to
tell its age, there was no more to be said.
label: sadness

text:
At last the Mouse, who seemed to be a person of authority among them,
called out, “Sit down, all of you, and listen to me!

moment like a wild beast, screamed “Off with her head!
label: anger

text: Off—”
label: anger

text:
“Nonsense!” said Alice, very loudly and decidedly, and the Queen was
silent.
label: anger

text:
The King laid his hand upon her arm, and timidly said “Consider, my
dear: she is only a child!”
label: fear

text:
The Queen turned angrily away from him, and said to the Knave “Turn
them over!”
label: anger

text: The Knave did so, very carefully, with one foot.
label: neutral

text:
“Get up!” said the Queen, in a shrill, loud voice, and the three
gardeners instantly jumped up, and began bowing to the King, the Queen,
the royal children, and everybody else.
label: neutral

text: “Leave off that!” screamed the Queen.
label: anger

text:
“You make me giddy.” And then,
turning to the rose-tree, she went on, “What _have_ you been doing
here?”
label: joy

text:
“May it please your Majesty,” said Two, in a very humble tone, going
down on one knee as he spoke, “we were trying—”
label: neutral

text: “_I_ see!” said the Queen, who had meanwhile been examining the roses.
label: surprise

text:
“Off with their heads!” and the procession moved on, three of the
soldiers remaining behind to execute the unfortunate gardeners, who ran
to Alice for protection.
label: fear

text:
“You shan’t be beheaded!” said Alice, and she put them into a large
flower-pot that stood near.
label: anger

text:
The three soldiers wandered about for a
minute or two, looking for them, and then quietly marched off after the
others.
label: neutral

text: “Are their heads off?” shouted the Queen.
label: anger

text:
“Their heads are gone, if it please your Majesty!” the soldiers shouted
in reply.
label: anger

text: “That’s right!” shouted the Queen.
label: anger

text: “Can you play croquet?”
label: neutral

text:
The soldiers were silent, and looked at Alice, as the question was
evidently meant for her.
label: disgust

text: “Yes!” shouted Alice.
label: anger

text:
“Come on, then!” roared the Queen, and Alice joined the procession,
wondering very much what would happen next.
label: fear

text: “It’s—it’s a very fine day!” said a timid voice at her side.
label: fear

text:
She was
walking by the White Rabbit, who was peeping anxiously into her face.
label: fear

text: “Very,” said Alice: “—where’s the Duchess?”
label: neutral

text: “Hush!
label: disgust

text: Hush!” said the Rabbit in a low, hurried tone.
label: disgust

text:
He looked
anxiously over his shoulder as he spoke, and then raised himself upon
tiptoe, put his mouth close to her ear, and whispered “She’s under
sentence of execution.”
label: disgust

text: “What for?” said Alice.
label: surprise

text: “Did you say ‘What a pity!’?” the Rabbit asked.
label: disgust

text: “No, I didn’t,” said Alice: “I don’t think it’s at all a pity.
label: disgust

text:
I said
‘What for?’”
label: surprise

text: “She boxed the Queen’s ears—” the Rabbit began.
label: disgust

text:
Alice gave a little
scream of laughter.
label: joy

text:
“Oh, hush!” the Rabbit whispered in a frightened
tone.
label: fear

text: “The Queen will hear you!
label: joy

text:
You see, she came rather late, and the
Queen said—”
label: neutral

text:
“Get to your places!” shouted the Queen in a voice of thunder, and
people began running about in all directions, tumbling up against each
other; however, they got settled down in a minute or two, and the game
began.
label: anger

text:
Alice thought she had never seen such a curious croquet-ground
in her life; it was all ridges and furrows; the balls were live
hedgehogs, the mallets live flamingoes, and the soldiers had to double
themselves up and to stand on their hands and feet, to make the arches.
label: surprise

text:
The chief difficulty Alice found at first was in managing her flamingo:
she succeeded in getting its body tucked away, comfortably enough,
under her arm, with its legs hanging down, but generally, just as she
had got its neck nicely straightened out, and was going to give the
hedgehog a blow with its head, it _would_ twist itself round and look
up in her face, with such a puzzled expression that she could not help
bursting out laughing: and when she had got its head down, and was
going to begin again, it was very provoking to find that the hedgehog
had unrolled itself, and was in the act of crawling away: besides all
this, there was generally a ridge or furrow in the way wherever she
wanted to send the hedgehog to, and, as the doubled-up soldiers were
always getting up and walking off to other parts of the ground, Alice
soon came to the conclusion that it was a very difficult game indeed.
label: neutral

text:
The players all played at once without waiting for turns, quarrelling
all the while, and fighting for the hedgehogs; and in a very short time
the Queen was in a furious passion, and went stamping about, and
shouting “Off with his head!” or “Off with her head!” about once in a
minute.
label: anger

text:
Alice began to feel very uneasy: to be sure, she had not as yet had any
dispute with the Queen, but she knew that it might happen any minute,
“and then,” thought she, “what would become of me?
label: fear

text:
They’re dreadfully
fond of beheading people here; the great wonder is, that there’s any
one left alive!”
label: fear

text:
She was looking about for some way of escape, and wondering whether she
could get away without being seen, when she noticed a curious
appearance in the air: it puzzled her very much at first, but, after
watching it a minute or two, she made it out to be a grin, and she said
to herself “It’s the Cheshire Cat: now I shall have somebody to talk
to.”
label: neutral

text:
“How are you getting on?” said the Cat, as soon as there was mouth
enough for it to speak with.
label: surprise

text: Alice waited till the eyes appeared, and then nodded.
label: neutral

text:
“It’s no use
speaking to it,” she thought, “till its ears have come, or at least one
of them.” In another minute the whole head appeared, and then Alice put
down her flamingo, and began an account of the game, feeling very glad
she had someone to listen to her.
label: joy

text:
The Cat seemed to think that there
was enough of it now in sight, and no more of it appeared.
label: neutral

text:
“I don’t think they play at all fairly,” Alice began, in rather a
complaining tone, “and they all quarrel so dreadfully one can’t hear
oneself speak—and they don’t seem to have any rules in particular; at
least, if there are, nobody attends to them—and you’ve no idea how
confusing it is all the things being alive; for instance, there’s the
arch I’ve got to go through next walking about at the other end of the
ground—and I should have croqueted the Queen’s hedgehog just now, only
it ran away when it saw mine coming!”
label: surprise

text: “How do you like the Queen?” said the Cat in a low voice.
label: neutral

text:
“Not at all,” said Alice: “she’s so extremely—” Just then she noticed
that the Queen was close behind her, listening: so she went on,
“—likely to win, that it’s hardly worth while finishing the game.”
label: surprise

text: The Queen smiled and passed on.
label: joy

text:
“Who _are_ you talking to?” said the King, going up to Alice, and
looking at the Cat’s head with great curiosity.
label: neutral

text:
“It’s a friend of mine—a Cheshire Cat,” said Alice: “allow me to
introduce it.”
label: neutral

text:
“I don’t like the look of it at all,” said the King: “however, it may
kiss my hand if it likes.”
label: disgust

text: “I’d rather not,” the Cat remarked.
label: neutral

text:
“Don’t be impertinent,” said the King, “and don’t look at me like
that!” He got behind Alice as he spoke.
label: neutral

text: “A cat may look at a king,” said Alice.
label: disgust

text:
“I’ve read that in some book,
but I don’t remember where.”
label: neutral

text:
“Well, it must be removed,” said the King very decidedly, and he called
the Queen, who was passing at the moment, “My dear!
label: sadness

text:
I wish you would
have this cat removed!”
label: sadness

text:
The Queen had only one way of settling all difficulties, great or
small.
label: neutral

text: “Off with his head!” she said, without even looking round.
label: anger

text:
“I’ll fetch the executioner myself,” said the King eagerly, and he
hurried off.
label: neutral

text:
Alice thought she might as well go back, and see how the game was going
on, as she heard the Queen’s voice in the distance, screaming with
passion.
label: neutral

text:
She had already heard her sentence three of the players to be
executed for having missed their turns, and she did not like the look
of things at all, as the game was in such confusion that she never knew
whether it was her turn or not.
label: disgust

text: So she went in search of her hedgehog.
label: neutral

text:
The hedgehog was engaged in a fight with another hedgehog, which seemed
to Alice an excellent opportunity for croqueting one of them with the
other: the only difficulty was, that her flamingo was gone across to
the other side of the garden, where Alice could see it trying in a
helpless sort of way to fly up into a tree.
label: neutral

text:
By the time she had caught the flamingo and brought it back, the fight
was over, and both the hedgehogs were out of sight: “but it doesn’t
matter much,” thought Alice, “as all the arches are gone from this side
of the ground.” So she tucked it away under her arm, that it might not
escape again, and went back for a little more conversation with her
friend.
label: neutral

text:
When she got back to the Cheshire Cat, she was surprised to find quite
a large crowd collected round it: there was a dispute going on between
the executioner, the King, and the Queen, who were all talking at once,
while all the rest were quite silent, and looked very uncomfortable.
label: surprise

text:
The moment Alice appeared, she was appealed to by all three to settle
the question, and they repeated their arguments to her, though, as they
all spoke at once, she found it very hard indeed to make out exactly
what they said.
label: neutral

text:
The executioner’s argument was, that you couldn’t cut off a head unless
there was a body to cut it off from: that he had never had to do such a
thing before, and he wasn’t going to begin at _his_ time of life.
label: neutral

text:
The King’s argument was, that anything that had a head could be
beheaded, and that you weren’t to talk nonsense.
label: anger

text:
The Queen’s argument was, that if something wasn’t done about it in
less than no time she’d have everybody executed, all round.
label: neutral

text:
(It was
this last remark that had made the whole party look so grave and
anxious.)
label: fear

text:
Alice could think of nothing else to say but “It belongs to the
Duchess: you’d better ask _her_ about it.”
label: neutral

text:
“She’s in prison,” the Queen said to the executioner: “fetch her here.”
And the executioner went off like an arrow.
label: anger

text:
The Cat’s head began fading away the moment he was gone, and, by the
time he had come back with the Duchess, it had entirely disappeared; so
the King and the executioner ran wildly up and down looking for it,
while the rest of the party went back to the game.
label: fear

text: CHAPTER IX.
label: neutral

text: The Mock Turtle’s Story
label: neutral

text:
“You can’t think how glad I am to see you again, you dear old thing!”
said the Duchess, as she tucked her arm affectionately into Alice’s,
and they walked off together.
label: joy

text:
Alice was very glad to find her in such a pleasant temper, and thought
to herself that perhaps it was only the pepper that had made her so
savage when they met in the kitchen.
label: joy

text:
“When _I’m_ a Duchess,” she said to herself, (not in a very hopeful
tone though), “I won’t have any pepper in my kitchen _at all_.
label: neutral

text:
Soup
does very well without—Maybe it’s always pepper that makes people
hot-tempered,” she went on, very much pleased at having found out a new
kind of rule, “and vinegar that makes them sour—and camomile that makes
them bitter—and—and barley-sugar and such things that make children
sweet-tempered.
label: disgust

text:
I only wish people knew _that_: then they wouldn’t be
so stingy about it, you know—”
label: anger

text:
She had quite forgotten the Duchess by this time, and was a little
startled when she heard her voice close to her ear.
label: surprise

text:
“You’re thinking
about something, my dear, and that makes you forget to talk.
label: disgust

text:
I can’t
tell you just now what the moral of that is, but I shall remember it in
a bit.”
label: neutral

text: “Perhaps it hasn’t one,” Alice ventured to remark.
label: neutral

text: “Tut, tut, child!” said the Duchess.
label: anger

text:
“Everything’s got a moral, if only
you can find it.” And she squeezed herself up closer to Alice’s side as
she spoke.
label: neutral

text:
Alice did not much like keeping so close to her: first, because the
Duchess was _very_ ugly; and secondly, because she was exactly the
right height to rest her chin upon Alice’s shoulder, and it was an
uncomfortably sharp chin.
label: disgust

text:
However, she did not like to be rude, so she
bore it as well as she could.
label: neutral

text:
“The game’s going on rather better now,” she said, by way of keeping up
the conversation a little.
label: neutral

text:
“’Tis so,” said the Duchess: “and the moral of that is—‘Oh, ’tis love,
’tis love, that makes the world go round!’”
label: neutral

text:
“Somebody said,” Alice whispered, “that it’s done by everybody minding
their own business!”
label: anger

text: “Ah, well!
label: joy

text:
It means much the same thing,” said the Duchess, digging her
sharp little chin into Alice’s shoulder as she added, “and the moral of
_that_ is—‘Take care of the sense, and the sounds will take care of
themselves.’”
label: neutral

text:
“How fond she is of finding morals in things!” Alice thought to
herself.
label: disgust

text:
“I dare say you’re wondering why I don’t put my arm round your waist,”
the Duchess said after a pause: “the reason is, that I’m doubtful about
the temper of your flamingo.
label: surprise

text: Shall I try the experiment?”
label: neutral

text:
“He might bite,” Alice cautiously replied, not feeling at all anxious
to have the experiment tried.
label: fear

text: “Very true,” said the Duchess: “flamingoes and mustard both bite.
label: neutral

text:
And
the moral of that is—‘Birds of a feather flock together.’”
label: neutral

text: “Only mustard isn’t a bird,” Alice remarked.
label: neutral

text:
“Right, as usual,” said the Duchess: “what a clear way you have of
putting things!”
label: surprise

text: “It’s a mineral, I _think_,” said Alice.
label: neutral

text:
“Of course it is,” said the Duchess, who seemed ready to agree to
everything that Alice said; “there’s a large mustard-mine near here.
label: neutral

text:
And the moral of that is—‘The more there is of mine, the less there is
of yours.’”
label: neutral

text:
“Oh, I know!” exclaimed Alice, who had not attended to this last
remark, “it’s a vegetable.
label: surprise

text: It doesn’t look like one, but it is.”
label: neutral

text:
“I quite agree with you,” said the Duchess; “and the moral of that
is—‘Be what you would seem to be’—or if you’d like it put more
simply—‘Never imagine yourself not to be otherwise than what it might
appear to others that what you were or might have been was not
otherwise than what you had been would have appeared to them to be
otherwise.’”
label: neutral

text:
“I think I should understand that better,” Alice said very politely,
“if I had it written down: but I can’t quite follow it as you say it.”
label: neutral

text:
“That’s nothing to what I could say if I chose,” the Duchess replied,
in a pleased tone.
label: joy

text:
“Pray don’t trouble yourself to say it any longer than that,” said
Alice.
label: neutral

text: “Oh, don’t talk about trouble!” said the Duchess.
label: fear

text:
“I make you a present
of everything I’ve said as yet.”
label: neutral

text: “A cheap sort of present!” thought Alice.
label: surprise

text:
“I’m glad they don’t give
birthday presents like that!” But she did not venture to say it out
loud.
label: joy

text:
“Thinking again?” the Duchess asked, with another dig of her sharp
little chin.
label: disgust

text:
“I’ve a right to think,” said Alice sharply, for she was beginning to
feel a little worried.
label: fear

text:
“Just about as much right,” said the Duchess, “as pigs have to fly; and
the m—”
label: neutral

text:
But here, to Alice’s great surprise, the Duchess’s voice died away,
even in the middle of her favourite word ‘moral,’ and the arm that was
linked into hers began to tremble.
label: surprise

text:
Alice looked up, and there stood the
Queen in front of them, with her arms folded, frowning like a
thunderstorm.
label: anger

text: “A fine day, your Majesty!” the Duchess began in a low, weak voice.
label: neutral

text:
“Now, I give you fair warning,” shouted the Queen, stamping on the
ground as she spoke; “either you or your head must be off, and that in
about half no time!
label: neutral

text: Take your choice!”
label: anger

text: The Duchess took her choice, and was gone in a moment.
label: sadness

text:
“Let’s go on with the game,” the Queen said to Alice; and Alice was too
much frightened to say a word, but slowly followed her back to the
croquet-ground.
label: fear

text:
The other guests had taken advantage of the Queen’s absence, and were
resting in the shade: however, the moment they saw her, they hurried
back to the game, the Queen merely remarking that a moment’s delay
would cost them their lives.
label: anger

text:
All the time they were playing the Queen never left off quarrelling
with the other players, and shouting “Off with his head!” or “Off with
her head!” Those whom she sentenced were taken into custody by the
soldiers, who of course had to leave off being arches to do this, so
that by the end of half an hour or so there were no arches left, and
all the players, except the King, the Queen, and Alice, were in custody
and under sentence of execution.
label: anger

text:
Then the Queen left off, quite out of breath, and said to Alice, “Have
you seen the Mock Turtle yet?”
label: neutral

text: “No,” said Alice.
label: neutral

text: “I don’t even know what a Mock Turtle is.”
label: neutral

text: “It’s the thing Mock Turtle Soup is made from,” said the Queen.
label: neutral

text: “I never saw one, or heard of one,” said Alice.
label: neutral

text: “Come on, then,” said the Queen, “and he shall tell you his history.”
label: neutral

text:
As they walked off together, Alice heard the King say in a low voice,
to the company generally, “You are all pardoned.” “Come, _that’s_ a
good thing!” she said to herself, for she had felt quite unhappy at the
number of executions the Queen had ordered.
label: sadness

text: They very soon came upon a Gryphon, lying fast asleep in the sun.
label: fear

text:
(If
you don’t know what a Gryphon is, look at the picture.)
label: neutral

text:
“Up, lazy
thing!” said the Queen, “and take this young lady to see the Mock
Turtle, and to hear his history.
label: neutral

text:
I must go back and see after some
executions I have ordered;” and she walked off, leaving Alice alone
with the Gryphon.
label: anger

text:
Alice did not quite like the look of the creature,
but on the whole she thought it would be quite as safe to stay with it
as to go after that savage Queen: so she waited.
label: neutral

text:
The Gryphon sat up and rubbed its eyes: then it watched the Queen till
she was out of sight: then it chuckled.
label: joy

text:
“What fun!” said the Gryphon,
half to itself, half to Alice.
label: joy

text: “What _is_ the fun?” said Alice.
label: neutral

text: “Why, _she_,” said the Gryphon.
label: surprise

text:
“It’s all her fancy, that: they never
executes nobody, you know.
label: neutral

text: Come on!”
label: anger

text:
“Everybody says ‘come on!’ here,” thought Alice, as she went slowly
after it: “I never was so ordered about in all my life, never!”
label: anger

text:
They had not gone far before they saw the Mock Turtle in the distance,
sitting sad and lonely on a little ledge of rock, and, as they came
nearer, Alice could hear him sighing as if his heart would break.
label: sadness

text:
She
pitied him deeply.
label: disgust

text:
“What is his sorrow?” she asked the Gryphon, and the
Gryphon answered, very nearly in the same words as before, “It’s all
his fancy, that: he hasn’t got no sorrow, you know.
label: sadness

text: Come on!”
label: anger

text:
So they went up to the Mock Turtle, who looked at them with large eyes
full of tears, but said nothing.
label: disgust

text:
“This here young lady,” said the Gryphon, “she wants for to know your
history, she do.”
label: neutral

text:
“I’ll tell it her,” said the Mock Turtle in a deep, hollow tone: “sit
down, both of you, and don’t speak a word till I’ve finished.”
label: neutral

text: So they sat down, and nobody spoke for some minutes.
label: disgust

text:
Alice thought to
herself, “I don’t see how he can _ever_ finish, if he doesn’t begin.”
But she waited patiently.
label: neutral

text:
“Once,” said the Mock Turtle at last, with a deep sigh, “I was a real
Turtle.”
label: neutral

text:
These words were followed by a very long silence, broken only by an
occasional exclamation of “Hjckrrh!” from the Gryphon, and the constant
heavy sobbing of the Mock Turtle.
label: sadness

text:
Alice was very nearly getting up and
saying, “Thank you, sir, for your interesting story,” but she could not
help thinking there _must_ be more to come, so she sat still and said
nothing.
label: neutral

text:
“When we were little,” the Mock Turtle went on at last, more calmly,
though still sobbing a little now and then, “we went to school in the
sea.
label: neutral

text: The master was an old Turtle—we used to call him Tortoise—”
label: neutral

text: “Why did you call him Tortoise, if he wasn’t one?” Alice asked.
label: surprise

text:
“We called him Tortoise because he taught us,” said the Mock Turtle
angrily: “really you are very dull!”
label: anger

text:
“You ought to be ashamed of yourself for asking such a simple
question,” added the Gryphon; and then they both sat silent and looked
at poor Alice, who felt ready to sink into the earth.
label: fear

text:
At last the
Gryphon said to the Mock Turtle, “Drive on, old fellow!
label: neutral

text:
Don’t be all
day about it!” and he went on in these words:
label: anger

text: “Yes, we went to school in the sea, though you mayn’t believe it—”
label: fear

text: “I never said I didn’t!” interrupted Alice.
label: anger

text: “You did,” said the Mock Turtle.
label: neutral

text: “Hold your tongue!” added the Gryphon, before Alice could speak again.
label: anger

text: The Mock Turtle went on.
label: neutral

text: “We had the best of educations—in fact, we went to school every day—”
label: neutral

text:
“_I’ve_ been to a day-school, too,” said Alice; “you needn’t be so
proud as all that.”
label: neutral

text: “With extras?” asked the Mock Turtle a little anxiously.
label: fear

text: “Yes,” said Alice, “we learned French and music.”
label: neutral

text: “And washing?” said the Mock Turtle.
label: neutral

text: “Certainly not!” said Alice indignantly.
label: anger

text: “Ah!
label: surprise

text:
then yours wasn’t a really good school,” said the Mock Turtle in a
tone of great relief.
label: neutral

text:
“Now at _ours_ they had at the end of the bill,
‘French, music, _and washing_—extra.’”
label: neutral

text:
“You couldn’t have wanted it much,” said Alice; “living at the bottom
of the sea.”
label: neutral

text: “I couldn’t afford to learn it.” said the Mock Turtle with a sigh.
label: sadness

text:
“I
only took the regular course.”
label: neutral

text: “What was that?” inquired Alice.
label: surprise

text:
“Reeling and Writhing, of course, to begin with,” the Mock Turtle
replied; “and then the different branches of Arithmetic—Ambition,
Distraction, Uglification, and Derision.”
label: disgust

text: “I never heard of ‘Uglification,’” Alice ventured to say.
label: neutral

text: “What is it?”
label: surprise

text: The Gryphon lifted up both its paws in surprise.
label: surprise

text: “What!
label: surprise

text:
Never heard of
uglifying!” it exclaimed.
label: disgust

text: “You know what to beautify is, I suppose?”
label: neutral

text: “Yes,” said Alice doubtfully: “it means—to—make—anything—prettier.”
label: fear

text:
“Well, then,” the Gryphon went on, “if you don’t know what to uglify
is, you _are_ a simpleton.”
label: neutral

text:
Alice did not feel encouraged to ask any more questions about it, so
she turned to the Mock Turtle, and said “What else had you to learn?”
label: neutral

text:
“Well, there was Mystery,” the Mock Turtle replied, counting off the
subjects on his flappers, “—Mystery, ancient and modern, with
Seaography: then Drawling—the Drawling-master was an old conger-eel,
that used to come once a week: _he_ taught us Drawling, Stretching, and
Fainting in Coils.”
label: neutral

text: “What was _that_ like?” said Alice.
label: neutral

text:
“Well, I can’t show it you myself,” the Mock Turtle said: “I’m too
stiff.
label: disgust

text: And the Gryphon never learnt it.”
label: neutral

text:
“Hadn’t time,” said the Gryphon: “I went to the Classics master,
though.
label: neutral

text: He was an old crab, _he_ was.”
label: neutral

text:
“I never went to him,” the Mock Turtle said with a sigh: “he taught
Laughing and Grief, they used to say.”
label: neutral

text:
“So he did, so he did,” said the Gryphon, sighing in his turn; and both
creatures hid their faces in their paws.
label: neutral

text:
“And how many hours a day did you do lessons?” said Alice, in a hurry
to change the subject.
label: neutral

text:
“Ten hours the first day,” said the Mock Turtle: “nine the next, and so
on.”
label: neutral

text: “What a curious plan!” exclaimed Alice.
label: surprise

text:

her hand, and Alice guessed who it was, even before she got into the
court, by the way the people near the door began sneezing all at once.
label: neutral

text: “Give your evidence,” said the King.
label: neutral

text: “Shan’t,” said the cook.
label: neutral

text:
The King looked anxiously at the White Rabbit, who said in a low voice,
“Your Majesty must cross-examine _this_ witness.”
label: fear

text:
“Well, if I must, I must,” the King said, with a melancholy air, and,
after folding his arms and frowning at the cook till his eyes were
nearly out of sight, he said in a deep voice, “What are tarts made of?”
label: sadness

text: “Pepper, mostly,” said the cook.
label: neutral

text: “Treacle,” said a sleepy voice behind her.
label: neutral

text: “Collar that Dormouse,” the Queen shrieked out.
label: anger

text: “Behead that Dormouse!
label: anger

text: Turn that Dormouse out of court!
label: anger

text: Suppress him!
label: anger

text: Pinch him!
label: anger

text:
Off with his
whiskers!”
label: fear

text:
For some minutes the whole court was in confusion, getting the Dormouse
turned out, and, by the time they had settled down again, the cook had
disappeared.
label: neutral

text: “Never mind!” said the King, with an air of great relief.
label: neutral

text:
“Call the
next witness.” And he added in an undertone to the Queen, “Really, my
dear, _you_ must cross-examine the next witness.
label: fear

text:
It quite makes my
forehead ache!”
label: sadness

text:
Alice watched the White Rabbit as he fumbled over the list, feeling
very curious to see what the next witness would be like, “—for they
haven’t got much evidence _yet_,” she said to herself.
label: surprise

text:
Imagine her
surprise, when the White Rabbit read out, at the top of his shrill
little voice, the name “Alice!”
label: surprise

text: CHAPTER XII.
label: neutral

text: Alice’s Evidence
label: neutral

text:
“Here!” cried Alice, quite forgetting in the flurry of the moment how
large she had grown in the last few minutes, and she jumped up in such
a hurry that she tipped over the jury-box with the edge of her skirt,
upsetting all the jurymen on to the heads of the crowd below, and there
they lay sprawling about, reminding her very much of a globe of
goldfish she had accidentally upset the week before.
label: neutral

text:
“Oh, I _beg_ your pardon!” she exclaimed in a tone of great dismay, and
began picking them up again as quickly as she could, for the accident
of the goldfish kept running in her head, and she had a vague sort of
idea that they must be collected at once and put back into the
jury-box, or they would die.
label: neutral

text:
“The trial cannot proceed,” said the King in a very grave voice, “until
all the jurymen are back in their proper places—_all_,” he repeated
with great emphasis, looking hard at Alice as he said so.
label: neutral

text:
Alice looked at the jury-box, and saw that, in her haste, she had put
the Lizard in head downwards, and the poor little thing was waving its
tail about in a melancholy way, being quite unable to move.
label: sadness

text:
She soon
got it out again, and put it right; “not that it signifies much,” she
said to herself; “I should think it would be _quite_ as much use in the
trial one way up as the other.”
label: neutral

text:
As soon as the jury had a little recovered from the shock of being
upset, and their slates and pencils had been found and handed back to
them, they set to work very diligently to write out a history of the
accident, all except the Lizard, who seemed too much overcome to do
anything but sit with its mouth open, gazing up into the roof of the
court.
label: neutral

text: “What do you know about this business?” the King said to Alice.
label: neutral

text: “Nothing,” said Alice.
label: neutral

text: “Nothing _whatever?_” persisted the King.
label: neutral

text: “Nothing whatever,” said Alice.
label: neutral

text: “That’s very important,” the King said, turning to the jury.
label: neutral

text:
They were
just beginning to write this down on their slates, when the White
Rabbit interrupted: “_Un_important, your Majesty means, of course,” he
said in a very respectful tone, but frowning and making faces at him as
he spoke.
label: anger

text:
“_Un_important, of course, I meant,” the King hastily said, and went on
to himself in an undertone,
label: neutral

text:
“important—unimportant—unimportant—important—” as if he were trying
which word sounded best.
label: neutral
disgust

text:
At this moment the King, who had been for some time busily writing in
his note-book, cackled out “Silence!” and read out from his book, “Rule
Forty-two.
label: neutral

text: _All persons more than a mile high to leave the court_.”
label: neutral

text: Everybody looked at Alice.
label: neutral

text: “_I’m_ not a mile high,” said Alice.
label: neutral

text: “You are,” said the King.
label: neutral

text: “Nearly two miles high,” added the Queen.
label: surprise

text:
“Well, I shan’t go, at any rate,” said Alice: “besides, that’s not a
regular rule: you invented it just now.”
label: neutral

text: “It’s the oldest rule in the book,” said the King.
label: neutral

text: “Then it ought to be Number One,” said Alice.
label: neutral

text: The King turned pale, and shut his note-book hastily.
label: disgust

text:
“Consider your
verdict,” he said to the jury, in a low, trembling voice.
label: fear

text:
“There’s more evidence to come yet, please your Majesty,” said the
White Rabbit, jumping up in a great hurry; “this paper has just been
picked up.”
label: neutral

text: “What’s in it?” said the Queen.
label: surprise

text:
“I haven’t opened it yet,” said the White Rabbit, “but it seems to be a
letter, written by the prisoner to—to somebody.”
label: neutral

text:
“It must have been that,” said the King, “unless it was written to
nobody, which isn’t usual, you know.”
label: neutral

text: “Who is it directed to?” said one of the jurymen.
label: neutral

text:
“It isn’t directed at all,” said the White Rabbit; “in fact, there’s
nothing written on the _outside_.” He unfolded the paper as he spoke,
and added “It isn’t a letter, after all: it’s a set of verses.”
label: neutral

text: “Are they in the prisoner’s handwriting?” asked another of the jurymen.
label: neutral

text:
“No, they’re not,” said the White Rabbit, “and that’s the queerest
thing about it.” (The jury all looked puzzled.)
label: neutral

text: “He must have imitated somebody else’s hand,” said the King.
label: disgust

text:
(The jury
all brightened up again.)
label: joy

text:
“Please your Majesty,” said the Knave, “I didn’t write it, and they
can’t prove I did: there’s no name signed at the end.”
label: neutral

text:
“If you didn’t sign it,” said the King, “that only makes the matter
worse.
label: disgust

text:
You _must_ have meant some mischief, or else you’d have signed
your name like an honest man.”
label: neutral

text:
There was a general clapping of hands at this: it was the first really
clever thing the King had said that day.
label: neutral

text: “That _proves_ his guilt,” said the Queen.
label: neutral

text: “It proves nothing of the sort!” said Alice.
label: anger

text:
“Why, you don’t even know
what they’re about!”
label: surprise

text: “Read them,” said the King.
label: neutral

text: The White Rabbit put on his spectacles.
label: disgust

text:
“Where shall I begin, please
your Majesty?” he asked.
label: fear

text:
“Begin at the beginning,” the King said gravely, “and go on till you
come to the end: then stop.”
label: fear

text: These were the verses the White Rabbit read:—
label: neutral

text:
“They told me you had been to her,
    And mentioned me to him:
She gave me a good character,
    But said I could not swim.
label: neutral

text:
He sent them word I had not gone
    (We know it to be true):
If she should push the matter on,
    What would become of you?
label: fear

text:
I gave her one, they gave him two,
    You gave us three or more;
They all returned from him to you,
    Though they were mine before.
label: neutral

text:
If I or she should chance to be
    Involved in this affair,
He trusts to you to set them free,
    Exactly as we were.
label: joy

text:
My notion was that you had been
    (Before she had this fit)
An obstacle that came between
    Him, and ourselves, and it.
label: fear

text:
Don’t let him know she liked them best,
    For this must ever be
A secret, kept from all the rest,
    Between yourself and me.”
label: neutral

text:
“That’s the most important piece of evidence we’ve heard yet,” said the
King, rubbing his hands; “so now let the jury—”
label: neutral

text:
“If any one of them can explain it,” said Alice, (she had grown so
large in the last few minutes that she wasn’t a bit afraid of
interrupting him,) “I’ll give him sixpence.
label: neutral

text:
_I_ don’t believe there’s
an atom of meaning in it.”
label: surprise

text:
The jury all wrote down on their slates, “_She_ doesn’t believe there’s
an atom of meaning in it,” but none of them attempted to explain the
paper.
label: neutral

text:
“If there’s no meaning in it,” said the King, “that saves a world of
trouble, you know, as we needn’t try to find any.
label: neutral

text:
And yet I don’t
know,” he went on, spreading out the verses on his knee, and looking at
them with one eye; “I seem to see some meaning in them, after all.
label: neutral

text:
“—_said I could not swim_—” you can’t swim, can you?” he added, turning
to the Knave.
label: neutral

text: The Knave shook his head sadly.
label: sadness

text: “Do I look like it?” he said.
label: neutral

text:
(Which he
certainly did _not_, being made entirely of cardboard.)
label: neutral

text:
“All right, so far,” said the King, and he went on muttering over the
verses to himself: “‘_We know it to be true_—’ that’s the jury, of
course—‘_I gave her one, they gave him two_—’ why, that must be what he
did with the tarts, you know—”
label: neutral

text: “But, it goes on ‘_they all returned from him to you_,’” said Alice.
label: neutral

text:
“Why, there they are!” said the King triumphantly, pointing to the
tarts on the table.
label: surprise

text: “Nothing can be clearer than _that_.
label: neutral

text:
Then
again—‘_before she had this fit_—’ you never had fits, my dear, I
think?” he said to the Queen.
label: neutral

text:
“Never!” said the Queen furiously, throwing an inkstand at the Lizard
as she spoke.
label: anger

text:
(The unfortunate little Bill had left off writing on his
slate with one finger, as he found it made no mark; but he now hastily
began again, using the ink, that was trickling down his face, as long
as it lasted.)
label: neutral

text:
“Then the words don’t _fit_ you,” said the King, looking round the
court with a smile.
label: neutral

text: There was a dead silence.
label: sadness

text:
“It’s a pun!” the King added in an offended tone, and everybody
laughed, “Let the jury consider their verdict,” the King said, for
about the twentieth time that day.
label: joy

text: “No, no!” said the Queen.
label: fear

text: “Sentence first—verdict afterwards.”
label: neutral

text: “Stuff and nonsense!” said Alice loudly.
label: anger

text:
“The idea of having the
sentence first!”
label: anger

text: “Hold your tongue!” said the Queen, turning purple.
label: anger

text: “I won’t!” said Alice.
label: anger

text: “Off with her head!” the Queen shouted at the top of her voice.
label: anger

text:
Nobody
moved.
label: sadness

text:
“Who cares for you?” said Alice, (she had grown to her full size by
this time.)
label: neutral

text: “You’re nothing but a pack of cards!”
label: surprise

text:
At this the whole pack rose up into the air, and came flying down upon
her: she gave a little scream, half of fright and half of anger, and
tried to beat them off, and found herself lying on the bank, with her
head in the lap of her sister, who was gently brushing away some dead
leaves that had fluttered down from the trees upon her face.
label: fear

text:
“Wake up, Alice dear!” said her sister; “Why, what a long sleep you’ve
had!”
label: surprise

text:
“Oh, I’ve had such a curious dream!” said Alice, and she told her
sister, as well as she could remember them, all these strange
Adventures of hers that you have just been reading about; and when she
had finished, her sister kissed her, and said, “It _was_ a curious
dream, dear, certainly: but now run in to your tea; it’s getting late.”
So Alice got up and ran off, thinking while she ran, as well she might,
what a wonderful dream it had been.
label: surprise

text:
But her sister sat still just as she left her, leaning her head on her
hand, watching the setting sun, and thinking of little Alice and all
her wonderful Adventures, till she too began dreaming after a fashion,
and this was her dream:—
label: neutral

text:
First, she dreamed of little Alice herself, and once again the tiny
hands were clasped upon her knee, and the bright eager eyes were
looking up into hers—she could hear the very tones of her voice, and
see that queer little toss of her head to keep back the wandering hair
that _would_ always get into her eyes—and still as she listened, or
seemed to listen, the whole place around her became alive with the
strange creatures of her little sister’s dream.
label: neutral

text:
The long grass rustled at her feet as the White Rabbit hurried by—the
frightened Mouse splashed his way through the neighbouring pool—she
could hear the rattle of the teacups as the March Hare and his friends
shared their never-ending meal, and the shrill voice of the Queen
ordering off her unfortunate guests to execution—once more the pig-baby
was sneezing on the Duchess’s knee, while plates and dishes crashed
around it—once more the shriek of the Gryphon, the squeaking of the
Lizard’s slate-pencil, and the choking of the suppressed guinea-pigs,
filled the air, mixed up with the distant sobs of the miserable Mock
Turtle.
label: sadness

text:
So she sat on, with closed eyes, and half believed herself in
Wonderland, though she knew she had but to open them again, and all
would change to dull reality—the grass would be only rustling in the
wind, and the pool rippling to the waving of the reeds—the rattling
teacups would change to tinkling sheep-bells, and the Queen’s shrill
cries to the voice of the shepherd boy—and the sneeze of the baby, the
shriek of the Gryphon, and all the other queer noises, would change
(she knew) to the confused clamour of the busy farm-yard—while the
lowing of the cattle in the distance would take the place of the Mock
Turtle’s heavy sobs.
label: sadness

text:
Lastly, she pictured to herself how this same little sister of hers
would, in the after-time, be herself a grown woman; and how she would
keep, through all her riper years, the simple and loving heart of her
childhood: and how she would gather about her other little children,
and make _their_ eyes bright and eager with many a strange tale,
perhaps even with the dream of Wonderland of long ago: and how she
would feel with all their simple sorrows, and find a pleasure in all
their simple joys, remembering her own child-life, and the happy summer
days.
label: joy

text: THE END
label: neutral
